      <abstract>
        <p>Rabbi Joshua M Davidson letter on Sen Joseph Lieberman's expression of religious conviction (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''What Joe Lieberman Can Do'' (editorial, Aug. 17):</p>
        <p>You say it has been a balancing act for Senator Lieberman ''to speak openly of his deep religious conviction without crossing the boundary that separates religion from the affairs of state.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''What Joe Lieberman Can Do'' (editorial, Aug. 17):</p>
        <p>You say it has been a balancing act for Senator Lieberman ''to speak openly of his deep religious conviction without crossing the boundary that separates religion from the affairs of state.''</p>
        <p>As a matter of personal taste, many Americans may prefer to separate the language of religious ideology from politics. But it would be a mistake to confuse the boundaries of personal taste with the boundaries of constitutional law.</p>
        <p>The First Amendment forbids government sanction of one set of religious beliefs over another, yet the same amendment guarantees the right of citizens, including politicians, to lobby for legislation reflecting their values, including values born of religious ideology.</p>
        <p>(Rabbi) JOSHUA M. DAVIDSON  New York, Aug. 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
